response:
Let's restate the polar equation and convert it into Cartesian coordinates.</think>
\[
r = \frac{1}{\sin \theta - \cos \theta}
\ i.e. \ \sin \theta - \cos \theta = \frac{1}{r}
\ i.e. \ \sin \theta - \cos \theta = \sin \theta /r - \cos \theta /r = y/r
\ i.e. \ 1 = \frac{y}{r} + \frac{x}{r} = \frac{y+x}{r}
\ i.e. \ r = y + x.
\text{Since}\ x^2 + y^2 = r^2,\text{we have from above}\ x^2 + y^2 = y + x.
\text{Rearranging we get}\ x^2 - x + y^2 - y = 0.
\text{Completing the square we have}\ x^2 - x +\frac 14 + y^2 - y +\frac 14 = \frac 12 \\
\text{or}\ (x-\frac 12)^2+(y-\frac 12)^2=\frac 12 = \left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\right)^2;
\text{which describes a circle centered at}\left(\frac 12,\frac 12\right)\text{with}\boxed{\text{radius}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}}.\end{array}
</think> <answer>B</answer>

